<li id='cid_78062'>
<div class="comment ">
<div class="commentbodycontainer"><p class="commentBody">
<span class="quoteStart quote"><!----></span>
Seems OK., but there are many soil types within the profile for this system,and what if the farm is well and truly established,and, thus a limitation in getting pipes below ground because of tree crop growth,and matters vineyard in the Murray River area of Australia!?The reason a rising water table and salt exuding to the soil is a major problem,is the potential for a sort of cave in and the remaining soil is riddled by salt.Applied electricity ,and even more understandings of copper and zinc planted in soil and connected as a functioning battery needs research.Salt in chemistry can be nuetralised,its a very lazy science world today,that doesn&#39;t recognise,if you reduce the salt pathways to surface,then you then have pathways deep into the soil from above.Micro needling the salt out of the way isn&#39;t cosmically impossible.Threading downwards with wire pipettes through the salt pathways needs investigation.Similar technologies to the above have been around in different configurations.Another problem remains of soil nutrient requirement under the harsher climates associated with these soil types.Atmospheric moisture should also be considered in the scheme directly. 6 out of 10 until further notice.
&nbsp;
<span class="quoteEnd quote"><!----></span>
</p>
</div><div class="commentMeta clearfix">
<div>philip travers</div>
